Who in all this world has an interest in Union College if not the students who are a part of it ? You have your say and say it war·m. Besides you will a 11 be Alumni soon, anyway. Union College belongs right where it is, 1·ight where it has been for a century. What would they do with Jackson's Garden, and the campus, and the grove, and the brook, and the woods the brook flows through ? What will they substitute for the beautiful view of the valley and the hills ? Romance and poetry and all the tender associations of our boyhood-all these things get crowded out of our lives in the struggle for bread and butter. Old Union has lived for a century in environments that can't be replaced elsewhere. The memory of the dead, the heart-throbs of the living, the voices of the past, the hopes of the future, all demand that where her walls have grown gray the Alma Mater remain forever. A. w. GLEASON.
